tric notions of the mind and its readability, legal doctrines of insanity and diminished culpability, and cultural stereotypes about race and gender shaped the ways in which legal professionals, mental health experts, and lay witnesses approached mental disability evidence, especially in cases carrying the death penalty. Using Texas as a case study, Deambrogio examines how these medical, legal, and cultural trends shaped psycho-legal debates in state criminal courts, while shedding light on the ways in which experts and lay actors' interpretations of "pathological" mental states influenced trial verdicts in capital cases. She shows that despite mounting pressures from advocates of the "rehabilitative penology," Texas courts maintained a punitive approach towards defendants allegedly affected by severe mental disabilities, while allowing for moralized views about personalities, habits, and lifestyle to influence psycho-legal assessments, in potentially prejudicial ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapital punishmentzTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aCriminal liabilityzTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aForensic psychiatryzTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aInsanity (Law)zTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aInsanity defensezTexasxHistoryy20th century. 7aLAW / Mental Health.2bisacsh  aForensic psychiatry.  acapital punishment.  acriminal responsibility.  acriminal trials.  afuture dangerousness.  ainsanity.  alegal history.  amasculinity.  amental illness.  aracial discrimination.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503637368?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637368/original  a978-3-